01:14.033 --> 01:15.934
[BIRDS CHIRPING]

01:30.167 --> 01:32.367
[ALARM BUZZES]

01:34.067 --> 01:35.467
[TURNS ALARM OFF]
Aah!

01:37.667 --> 01:39.701
Good morning, honey.

01:40.701 --> 01:43.300
BOTH:
Uugh...

01:43.300 --> 01:45.167
Mwah.

01:45.167 --> 01:48.100
Gee, you were great
last night, Al.

01:48.100 --> 01:51.000
You snored "Vaya con Dios"
in your sleep,

01:51.000 --> 01:52.000
while your nose hairs

01:52.000 --> 01:54.601
swayed romantically
to the beat.

01:54.601 --> 01:56.601
Yeah, you were pretty good
yourself, Peg.

01:56.601 --> 01:59.634
You sweated your silhouette
on the sheets.

01:59.634 --> 02:02.133
Oh, honey, let's do
something special tonight.

02:02.133 --> 02:04.267
You know, like we used to.

02:04.267 --> 02:06.400
You mean, like, I say
I don't wanna get married,

02:06.400 --> 02:08.868
and you
book the hall?

02:08.868 --> 02:10.000
Actually,
I was thinking

02:10.000 --> 02:11.501
we could find
someplace romantic

02:11.501 --> 02:13.868
and grope each other
in the dark.

02:13.868 --> 02:16.133
I couldn't find anything
in the dark.

02:16.133 --> 02:18.133
None of
the important parts

02:18.133 --> 02:21.667
are where
they used to be.

02:21.667 --> 02:23.133
Actually,
you couldn't find them

02:23.133 --> 02:27.100
in the light, either.
Ha, ha, ha.

02:27.100 --> 02:28.400
Pillow talk
all you want, Peg,

02:28.400 --> 02:29.901
but tonight's
bowling night.

02:29.901 --> 02:30.968
I can't be with you.

02:30.968 --> 02:34.234
I'm gonna have fun.

02:34.234 --> 02:35.534
Well, it's just as well.

02:35.534 --> 02:36.834
I'm gonna be pretty tired

02:36.834 --> 02:38.534
after a whole day
in the beauty parlor.

02:38.534 --> 02:39.834
Ha, ha, ha.

02:39.834 --> 02:41.701
I guess we can't
put it off any longer.

02:41.701 --> 02:43.634
We've both got a lot
to do. Come on.

02:43.634 --> 02:46.367
[AL GRUNTS]
[PEG SIGHS]

02:47.300 --> 02:48.601
Ah!

02:48.601 --> 02:50.534
What do you want
for breakfast, honey?

02:50.534 --> 02:51.534
Bacon and eggs?

02:51.534 --> 02:54.501
AL:
Ah, that'd be great.

02:54.501 --> 02:57.567
Good. While you're at it,
make me some too.

03:00.868 --> 03:02.667
[CUSTOMERS LAUGH]

03:02.667 --> 03:05.400
Ok, ok, ok, ok.
How 'bout this:

03:05.400 --> 03:06.667
How much would it take

03:06.667 --> 03:08.767
for you to do
the deed of darkness

03:08.767 --> 03:10.834
with Garry Shandling?

03:10.834 --> 03:13.934
[IN UNISON]
Ewww!

03:13.934 --> 03:15.334
Ten million.

03:15.334 --> 03:17.000
Twenty if he
wants to talk.

03:17.000 --> 03:19.601
[ALL LAUGH]

03:19.601 --> 03:22.133
How about
with Sonya's husband?

03:22.133 --> 03:24.501
[IN UNISON]
Ewww!

03:24.501 --> 03:27.934
We'll be with you
in a minute, Mrs. Rhoades.

03:27.934 --> 03:30.267
Oh...

03:30.267 --> 03:31.901
I'm kind of
nervous about this.

03:31.901 --> 03:35.000
I don't like new people
doing my hair.

03:35.000 --> 03:36.167
Why did Mr. Maurice

03:36.167 --> 03:40.033
have to get in that
slap fight with Julio?

03:40.033 --> 03:43.934
Don't worry, Marcy.
You'll look great.

03:43.934 --> 03:45.934
They're known for
tailoring each hairdo

03:45.934 --> 03:47.067
to the individual.

03:58.033 --> 04:01.300
So when was the last time
you got it, Peggy?
Hooh!

04:01.300 --> 04:02.934
Got it,
or got it good?

04:02.934 --> 04:03.934
[ALL LAUGH]

04:10.300 --> 04:12.734
Bleached.

04:12.734 --> 04:15.167
Siliconed.

04:15.167 --> 04:17.367
Kept.

04:17.367 --> 04:19.466
Happy.

04:21.466 --> 04:23.801
We're ready for you now,
Mrs. Rhoades,

04:23.801 --> 04:26.634
and we're gonna
make you beautiful.

04:26.634 --> 04:29.300
Do you sell insurance,
like at the airport?

04:32.467 --> 04:35.000
What's wrong with
our husbands, anyway?

04:35.000 --> 04:36.000
We go out
of our way

04:36.000 --> 04:37.801
to look beautiful
for them,

04:37.801 --> 04:39.133
and all we are

04:39.133 --> 04:42.033
are things to strike
a match on.

04:42.868 --> 04:43.868
I know.

04:43.868 --> 04:45.601
The only time
Al looks at me

04:45.601 --> 04:49.300
is when he wants
the cap off his beer.

04:49.300 --> 04:52.434
As if his teeth
aren't as good as mine!

04:56.000 --> 04:57.901
I'll tell ya, if I could get
the paper boy

04:57.901 --> 05:00.400
to come up for some
hot cocoa just once,

05:00.400 --> 05:03.534
I'd chuck my husband
in a second.

05:03.534 --> 05:05.100
Husbands.

05:05.100 --> 05:07.767
Actually, husbands
are wonderful...

05:07.767 --> 05:09.567
if they're not
your own.

05:12.567 --> 05:15.367
Well, they're grateful for
the smallest bit of attention.

05:15.367 --> 05:17.834
They're horny
as all get-out.

05:17.834 --> 05:19.200
And the best part of it:

05:19.200 --> 05:22.934
their spirit's
already been broken.

05:22.934 --> 05:27.033
Well, isn't breaking it
part of the fun?

05:27.033 --> 05:29.801
Oh, no. The fun is
the condos, the cars

05:29.801 --> 05:31.667
and the sex every night.
Ha, ha, ha!

05:31.667 --> 05:32.868
Oh, believe me,

05:32.868 --> 05:37.334
the best things in life
are someone else's.

05:37.334 --> 05:39.701
Well, when do you
get to see him?

05:39.701 --> 05:42.400
I mean,
how do husbands get out?

05:43.567 --> 05:46.100
Well, they may
appear stupid,

05:46.100 --> 05:49.367
but they usually find
an excuse to get away.

05:49.367 --> 05:50.634
Usually bowling.

05:53.501 --> 05:55.501
That's what
my current guy says.

05:55.501 --> 05:57.868
He is married
to a real shrew.

05:57.868 --> 06:00.767
She doesn't cook for him.
She doesn't clean for him.

06:06.000 --> 06:09.234
Well, it's so easy
to please a man who has nothing.

06:09.234 --> 06:10.234
Fry him up a burger,

06:10.234 --> 06:13.601
and you get a 24-inch Sony.

06:13.601 --> 06:16.901
Are you ready for your
color now, dear?

06:16.901 --> 06:17.934
Oh, sure.

06:17.934 --> 06:20.033
Now, don't let it
go red.

06:20.033 --> 06:21.033
He says that color

06:21.033 --> 06:23.200
makes him want
to throw up.

06:28.234 --> 06:32.400
Hey, everybody,
Al's cheating on Peggy!

06:34.634 --> 06:37.734
PEG [UPSTAIRS]:
Oh, Marcy, stop complaining.

06:37.734 --> 06:39.534
I think you look great.

06:58.868 --> 07:01.067
Oh, Marcy,
I'm really worried

07:01.067 --> 07:03.701
about Al and this
other woman.

07:03.701 --> 07:07.300
Oh, who cares about
your petty problems?

07:07.300 --> 07:09.267
I'm a helmet-head!

07:14.367 --> 07:16.801
BOY [ON STREET]:
Look! It's the Pope!

07:21.100 --> 07:22.734
Lick a wall socket!

07:25.667 --> 07:27.434
Don't worry.
Just do what I said,

07:27.434 --> 07:30.267
and your girlfriend
will never find out
you're cheating on her.

07:30.267 --> 07:32.701
Trust me.
I'm an expert.

07:32.701 --> 07:34.067
All right.
I'll see you tonight

07:34.067 --> 07:35.767
under the bleachers.

07:35.767 --> 07:37.834
Oh, and this time,

07:37.834 --> 07:41.133
leave your camera at home.
Thanks. Bye.

07:41.133 --> 07:43.701
Kelly, I wanna talk to you
about something.

07:43.701 --> 07:46.267
I'm a good girl,
Mommy.

07:46.267 --> 07:48.968
I said no camera.

07:48.968 --> 07:50.367
Oh, I don't care
what you do.

07:50.367 --> 07:51.734
This is about me.

07:51.734 --> 07:53.667
Bud, get lost.

07:57.334 --> 07:58.801
Honey, look.

07:58.801 --> 08:00.567
You've obviously
been "the other woman"

08:00.567 --> 08:01.567
ever since you learned

08:01.567 --> 08:03.868
to slit your diapers
up the side.

08:09.467 --> 08:10.734
But tell me,

08:10.734 --> 08:13.367
how come their girlfriends
never find out?

08:13.367 --> 08:14.968
Well, you know,

08:14.968 --> 08:17.000
people throw the word
"hussy" around,

08:17.000 --> 08:18.167
but they don't understand

08:18.167 --> 08:21.501
the research
and preparation involved.

08:21.501 --> 08:22.868
No guy walks
away from me

08:22.868 --> 08:25.667
without lessons in
the art of cover-up.

08:25.667 --> 08:28.901
And the number
of the free clinic.

08:36.634 --> 08:40.133
Go look in the mirror
and twitch.

08:40.133 --> 08:42.933
Anyway, the first thing
that I teach them

08:42.933 --> 08:44.434
is that a woman
can pick up the scent

08:44.434 --> 08:46.067
of another woman on her man.

08:46.067 --> 08:47.100
So, to get rid of it,

08:47.100 --> 08:49.033
I have them rub
their hands in the grass.

08:49.033 --> 08:50.667
Does he ask you to move,

08:50.667 --> 08:54.033
or does he
work around you?

08:54.033 --> 08:57.934
Is there no kennel
that will take him?

08:57.934 --> 08:59.200
Bud, please.

08:59.200 --> 09:00.934
We both know
your sister's not a tramp.

09:00.934 --> 09:02.400
She's just popular.

09:02.400 --> 09:06.534
Ok. Date's over.
Your smell's off him.

09:06.534 --> 09:07.701
Now what?

09:07.701 --> 09:10.434
[SIGHS]
Always make sure
they have an excuse.

09:10.434 --> 09:12.067
Somewhere
they've been. Um...

09:12.067 --> 09:14.000
The library,
their parole officer,

09:14.000 --> 09:15.634
the drunk tank.

09:15.634 --> 09:17.634
Bowling?

09:17.634 --> 09:19.567
Well, that works
for older guys.

09:19.567 --> 09:23.534
Hm. Your father's
out bowling tonight.

09:23.534 --> 09:25.167
Oh, well,
I mean--

09:25.167 --> 09:27.734
I meant people older
than Daddy.

09:27.734 --> 09:30.434
Are there any?

09:30.434 --> 09:32.667
Hey, Mom.

09:32.667 --> 09:34.267
Do you think
Dad's cheating on you?

09:34.267 --> 09:36.300
Oh, of course not.

09:36.300 --> 09:37.901
Good. 'Cause we
don't wanna see

09:37.901 --> 09:39.400
you and Dad
break up.

09:39.400 --> 09:42.901
We're almost like
a family here.

09:42.901 --> 09:45.234
You two should stay
together forever.

09:45.234 --> 09:46.400
However,

09:46.400 --> 09:48.434
if you find
that you can't,

09:48.434 --> 09:50.801
may I suggest
Mr. Rudnick, the butcher?

09:50.801 --> 09:52.067
He makes
a nice living.

09:52.067 --> 09:54.133
We'd always have
fresh meat on the table

09:54.133 --> 09:57.868
and season tickets
to the Cubs.

09:57.868 --> 10:01.801
Can't say I like the sound
of Bud Rudnick.

10:01.801 --> 10:04.400
But pound for pound,
he's the better father.

10:04.400 --> 10:06.367
Oh, wait.
Not so fast, Bud.

10:06.367 --> 10:07.400
I've been scoping out

10:07.400 --> 10:09.701
Mr. Fletcher,
the dry cleaner.

10:09.701 --> 10:13.734
He's got a Porsche,
cable TV and a bad heart.

10:18.334 --> 10:19.334
Rudnick.

10:19.334 --> 10:20.334
Fletcher.

10:20.334 --> 10:21.734
Rudnick!
Fletcher!

10:21.734 --> 10:23.434
Kids!

10:23.434 --> 10:26.334
Now, your father and I
love each other very much.

10:26.334 --> 10:28.100
And I'm gonna do
everything in my power

10:28.100 --> 10:30.234
to make sure
we stay together.

10:30.234 --> 10:32.467
Then what did you get us
all excited for?

10:33.834 --> 10:37.000
Is this another one
of your cruel jokes?

10:37.000 --> 10:38.033
Yeah, what are we,

10:38.033 --> 10:40.100
just playthings
for your amusement?

10:40.100 --> 10:42.000
Oh, that reminds me.
I'm late for my date.

10:46.834 --> 10:47.901
AL:
Hi, Kelly.

10:47.901 --> 10:49.000
Hey,

10:49.000 --> 10:52.300
what are you throwing
the grass on me for?

10:56.467 --> 10:59.534
KELLY:
'Cause I don't
wanna be a Rudnick.

10:59.534 --> 11:01.767
Hello, Al.

11:01.767 --> 11:04.634
How was, uh...
bowling?

11:04.634 --> 11:10.934
Well, Peg,
it was, uh...fine.

11:10.934 --> 11:13.634
Good.

11:13.634 --> 11:15.100
[SNIFFS WILDLY]

11:19.667 --> 11:20.834
[SNIFFS]

11:22.434 --> 11:24.701
Well, Peg,
what's next?

11:24.701 --> 11:26.033
We go out,
find a fire hydrant,

11:26.033 --> 11:28.067
lift our legs?

11:30.234 --> 11:31.434
I just wanted
to make sure

11:31.434 --> 11:34.667
all the smells
are where they should be.

11:34.667 --> 11:36.501
Ooh!

11:36.501 --> 11:39.300
And they are.

11:39.300 --> 11:42.601
Is that a burger
I smell on your breath?

11:42.601 --> 11:44.601
No, Peg,
it's our wedding cake.

11:44.601 --> 11:46.834
That's the last time
I ate.

11:46.834 --> 11:49.567
[TELEPHONE RINGS]

11:49.567 --> 11:51.334
What's going on
around here?

11:51.334 --> 11:52.868
I might ask you
the same thing,

11:52.868 --> 11:55.601
Mr. 24-inch Sony.

11:55.601 --> 11:57.067
Don't call me a TV
in my own home.

11:57.067 --> 12:00.200
You're a TV.

12:00.200 --> 12:04.234
BUD [UPSTAIRS]:
Dad, it's for you. Some woman.

12:05.767 --> 12:07.300
Hello.

12:07.300 --> 12:09.167
Yeah.

12:09.167 --> 12:10.534
Oh, yeah.
I guess I can make it.

12:10.534 --> 12:13.434
Ok, yeah, yeah.
Bye.

12:13.434 --> 12:15.400
That was
Jim Bauer's wife.

12:15.400 --> 12:17.868
It looks like he got some kind
of stomach flu or something.

12:17.868 --> 12:19.767
It looks like I got to
work for him at the store

12:19.767 --> 12:20.801
the rest of the week.

12:20.801 --> 12:22.033
Anything for supper?

12:22.033 --> 12:24.167
I hate you, Al.

12:26.033 --> 12:29.267
Toaster!

12:31.300 --> 12:32.934
[SIZZLING]

12:32.934 --> 12:35.000
PEG:
I'll show that woman
she's not the only one

12:35.000 --> 12:36.734
who can cook a burger.

12:36.734 --> 12:41.167
Oh, so...

12:41.167 --> 12:43.501
So you, like,
reverse it?

12:45.634 --> 12:48.167
It's called
"flipping it over."

12:48.167 --> 12:50.167
That way, it gets cooked
on both sides.

12:50.167 --> 12:51.968
Oh. Gee.

12:51.968 --> 12:55.167
I wonder if that would work
with pancakes?

12:57.200 --> 13:00.200
Oh, Marcy,
I can't believe it.

13:00.200 --> 13:01.934
I've taken the best years
of Al's life,

13:01.934 --> 13:04.701
and this is how
he thanks me.

13:04.701 --> 13:06.067
Peggy, I really
don't think

13:06.067 --> 13:07.801
Al's cheating on you.

13:07.801 --> 13:10.667
I took an impromptu poll
of all the women I know,

13:10.667 --> 13:13.200
and as far as
his desirability,

13:13.200 --> 13:18.067
Al ranked below Alf.

13:18.067 --> 13:19.634
Which means
they'd rather make love

13:19.634 --> 13:26.234
to a piece of cloth
with a man's hand in it...

13:26.234 --> 13:28.300
than with your husband.

13:28.300 --> 13:30.868
What if he is
cheatin' on me?

13:30.868 --> 13:32.534
Stand by your man...

13:32.534 --> 13:34.534
in court.

13:34.534 --> 13:35.634
Take him for
everything,

13:35.634 --> 13:37.567
and get yourself
another man.

13:37.567 --> 13:39.000
A real man.

13:39.000 --> 13:41.634
I don't want
a real man.

13:41.634 --> 13:43.167
I want Al.

13:47.167 --> 13:49.801
Why?

13:49.801 --> 13:52.000
Oh, I don't know.

13:52.000 --> 13:53.000
Have you ever had

13:53.000 --> 13:55.100
a favorite pair
of old shoes?

13:55.100 --> 13:56.701
They're boring
and ugly

13:56.701 --> 13:59.100
and stink
to high heaven.

13:59.100 --> 14:01.367
But they're yours,
you know?

14:01.367 --> 14:03.434
They're worn down
and broken in,

14:03.434 --> 14:05.234
and when you
put 'em on,

14:05.234 --> 14:07.234
it feels like
there's nothing there.

14:07.234 --> 14:12.000
Ha, ha, ha.
That's my Al.

14:12.000 --> 14:14.167
I've lost my
stinkin' Al.

14:14.167 --> 14:15.734
Aw...

14:15.734 --> 14:17.000
Not yet.

14:17.000 --> 14:19.534
I told you, I had Steve
wear a disguise

14:19.534 --> 14:22.367
and follow Al
since last night.

14:22.367 --> 14:24.000
He has nothing else
to do,

14:24.000 --> 14:28.000
because he won't go near me
with this hair.

14:33.968 --> 14:36.367
Hello, Peggy.

14:36.367 --> 14:37.834
Bee-woman.

14:41.634 --> 14:44.334
So, what'd ya find out
about Al?

14:44.334 --> 14:47.200
I found out that he has
the most pathetic life

14:47.200 --> 14:49.701
of any creature
on this planet...

14:49.701 --> 14:52.000
and has nicer hair
than my wife.

14:52.000 --> 14:53.100
Heh, heh, heh!

14:54.868 --> 14:56.033
[SNAPS FINGERS]

14:56.033 --> 14:58.234
Uh... Ahem...
Now for my report.

15:00.734 --> 15:04.601
"Subject arrived at work
at 7 p.m. last night.

15:04.601 --> 15:10.901
"Wept till 7:30.
Then turned on lights.

15:10.901 --> 15:14.300
"Inventory till 8:30.
Bathroom till 10.

15:16.434 --> 15:20.400
"10:07: Ate dinner consisting of
packaged condiments

15:20.400 --> 15:22.334
"he lifted from Barney Dog.

15:24.901 --> 15:29.067
"10:31: The mall
security guard comes by,

15:29.067 --> 15:30.534
"clubs me about the head
and ears

15:30.534 --> 15:31.834
and takes my watch."

15:34.467 --> 15:35.701
So from here on,

15:35.701 --> 15:38.734
I don't know what time
anything happens.

15:38.734 --> 15:39.834
"Went home."

15:42.767 --> 15:44.367
Looked at the
sleeping Klingon

15:44.367 --> 15:47.467
that used to be
my wife--

15:47.467 --> 15:49.767
Come on, lice-capade.

15:49.767 --> 15:51.601
Is he cheatin' on me
or not?

15:53.334 --> 15:56.167
Absolutely not.

15:56.167 --> 15:57.767
You are a liar.

15:57.767 --> 16:00.234
All you men
stick together.

16:00.234 --> 16:01.400
Yeah.

16:01.400 --> 16:03.834
You probably weren't even
watching Al.

16:03.834 --> 16:05.868
Where have you been?

16:05.868 --> 16:09.133
You got me.

16:09.133 --> 16:12.133
An old girlfriend,
Kathleen Turner, was in town.

16:12.133 --> 16:14.801
So I rubbed some
grime and lice on my body,

16:14.801 --> 16:17.334
and we went
dumpster hopping.

16:17.334 --> 16:19.601
Well, you hate my hair
so much,

16:19.601 --> 16:21.501
you'd really do that,
wouldn't you?

16:21.501 --> 16:23.868
Well...

16:23.868 --> 16:26.367
Yeah.

16:26.367 --> 16:29.067
Well, let's just see
Kathleen Turner

16:29.067 --> 16:30.801
make melon balls
for you.

16:30.801 --> 16:32.334
I'm sorry.

16:32.334 --> 16:33.801
I'm sorry!

16:36.467 --> 16:38.367
Hey, Peg.

16:38.367 --> 16:39.767
I just saw
Steve and Marcy.

16:39.767 --> 16:43.133
Boy, Marcy looks
ridiculous.

16:43.133 --> 16:44.133
Hi, Al.

16:44.133 --> 16:45.133
Honey, look.

16:45.133 --> 16:46.133
Look, look, look.

16:46.133 --> 16:47.701
I-- I made you
a hamburger,

